Incident.Summary: FMCSA North American Level III Inspection/Transporting Handgun In Vehicle

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
MVR Statement:

This incident was captured on body-worn and in-car mobile video recording equipment. G-31 is equipped with an in-car video/audio recording device. 

Neighborhood Check

Due to the incident, a neighborhood check was not conducted.

Scene Processing

A loaded Kahr CW9 (Serial # EH2670) with a full six (6) round magazine (total of seven (7) rounds) was recovered from above the driver’s visor The handgun, magazine, and ammunition were processed per MSP procedures on an MSP Form 63 and 67 and stored under PH # P-323238 at the Maryland State Police Westminster Barrack.

Suspect 

Wesley James McDaniel, DOB 10/08/1991, 5’06”, 150 lbs., W/M

Charges 

  • CR 4-203(a)(1)(v) Loaded Handgun In Vehicle

Narrative

On February 5, 2023, at approximately 1203 hours, I, Trooper First Class Mills # 6784 assigned to the Maryland State Police Westminster Barrack, was on patrol in the area of eastbound Maryland Route 140 east of Suffolk Road, Westminster, Carroll County, Maryland while operating marked Maryland State Police vehicle G-31. At this time, I observed a lime green International tow truck, hauling two sedans, traveling westbound without a company name or USDOT number affixed to the side. Due to the observed violation of the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration 390.21, I quickly made a U-turn and got behind the vehicle. I determined the International to be bearing Pennsylvania registration “WL27677”. I activated my emergency equipment to perform a traffic stop/inspection of the driver. The International came to a complete stop on westbound Maryland Route 140 east of Suffolk Road, Westminster, Carroll County, Maryland. I approached the International on the passenger side and attempted to make contact with the sole male driver, but due to the driver’s dog in the passenger seat, I walked around the truck to make contact with the driver on the driver’s side. While talking to the tow truck driver, he was identified by his Pennsylvania driver’s license as Wesley James McDaniel (DOB 10/08/1991 W/M.) I performed an FMCSA North American Standard Level III inspection. (I am trained to complete FMCSA North American Standard Level III inspections through the Maryland State Police Commercial Vehicle Enforcement Division (CVED) (Level 3 Inspection attached). McDaniel was able to produce all the requested documentation, including his driver’s license, DOT medical card, vehicle registration, and sales receipts for the two vehicles he was towing on the truck. McDaniel also advised he was coming from Reisterstown, Maryland, and headed back to his shop in Gettysburg, Pennsylvania.

Due to my training, knowledge, and experience of tow truck operators carrying firearms within their vehicles, I asked him if he had any form of self-protection inside the vehicle. McDaniel then advised me, “I do, I do. Now I don’t have, I have my license to carry for um, uh, PA. But I don’t have it for Maryland, so when I come down here, I don’t carry.” I asked if he had anything in the truck at the moment. McDaniel then stated, “I do have my weapon in the truck. Um, I don’t carry it on me when I come down here just because of the laws. So but when I come down here, I generally do have it with me.” I asked him where in the vehicle the weapon was, and McDaniel advised that the handgun was above his driver’s side visor. I asked McDaniel if the gun was in its case and if it was loaded, and McDaniel advised it was not in a case and it was loaded. Due to his statement, I asked him not to reach for anything and requested that he exit the vehicle, to which he complied. While McDaniel was outside the vehicle, I again asked him if he had a Maryland carry permit, and he stated, “I do not, I do not.” I asked him why he did not have a Maryland permit, and he stated, “I haven’t been able to get it yet. Um, I have, um, I’m, my record’s clean, clean as silk. I just haven’t been able to get it. I wanted to go for the class they had in Hampstead to do the Maryland carry, but I just, I just haven’t. Sunday is the only day I come down to Maryland. I, I don’t travel down this way a whole lot, cuz I don’t like, cuz, no offense, I don’t like the area. So um, I just don’t travel down this way.” I explained to McDaniel he cannot have the firearm in the vehicle in the manner he had it, McDaniel advised he understood. I frisked his person for any additional weapons, which yielded negative results. I did observe a holster on his right side, tucked inside his waistband. I asked McDaniel if he took the firearm out of the holster when I pulled him over, and he stated, “No sir, no sir.”  He went on to explain that when he crossed the Maryland line, he put the firearm in the visor, stating, “It was a bad procedure on my call. Um, you know, I should have put it in a lockbox and, and whatnot, you know. I’m coming down from Gettysburg, you know, and I just stuck it up there. It’s just a … (McDaniel did not finish his sentence and shrugged his shoulders.).” I asked McDaniel if there was a round in the chamber, and he stated, “Yes, absolutely.” I asked for his Pennsylvania carry permit, and he was able to provide it. I asked McDaniel if he had a case for the firearm in the truck, and he advised he did not. McDaniel did advise that the firearm was registered to him. I asked what the make of the firearm was, and McDaniel stated, “It’s a Kahr, K-A-H-R, nine (9) millimeter.” I asked how many rounds were in the firearm, and McDaniel stated, “Uh, it’s seven (7).” I then requested McDaniel walk back to the front of my patrol vehicle, to which he complied. I then asked if there was anything else in the vehicle I needed to be aware of, and McDaniel advised the only other thing in the vehicle was money. 

I asked McDaniel if I had his consent to search the vehicle, and he stated, “Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yes, yes. I have nothing to hide. No, I have nothing to hide. I had to make sure I understood what you were saying. I have nothing to hide. I told you where it's at, you can look in there for anything else that you want. Alls I got is money, and that so.” McDaniel explained his dog was friendly, and he did not have a leash for her. I confirmed with McDaniel that the firearm was in the visor above the driver's seat, and he stated, “Yes.”

I then conducted a search of the vehicle. While searching the vehicle, I observed a silver and black handgun in the visor, above the driver’s seat. I retrieved the handgun and observed it to be a Kahr, 9MM handgun. As I rendered the weapon safe, I ejected the magazine and locked the slide back, ejecting the round that was in the chamber. I notified the barrack and asked for a stolen check to be performed to ensure the handgun was not stolen. The rest of the search yielded no further contraband. 

At 1307 hours, I placed McDaniel under arrest for illegal possession of a loaded handgun in the vehicle. I immediately notified the barrack and searched his person for weapons and contraband, both with negative results. I did observe that McDaniel had a holster for the Kahr CW9 on his right side attached to his pants at the waist. (See attached pictures of the holster) 

I then transported McDaniel back to the Maryland State Police Westminster Barrack. Once at the barrack, I processed the firearm per MSP policy and documented the handgun, magazine, and ammunition on an MSP Form 63 and 67.  

The total number of 9mm rounds was seven (7).  

The number of 9mm rounds was verified by Sgt. Smith #2927.

McDaniel was then transported to the Carroll County Central Booking to see the commissioner. 

Case closed by arrest. 

All events occurred in Carroll County, Maryland.

Action Taken:

On 02/21/2023 at 13:00 hrs., I responded to the Golden Ring Barrack to conduct an operation test on the aforementioned firearm. The test result was completed. The firearm was found to be operable.

Case remains closed.
